The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | The key men
                                                   The key men
                      
	VIRAT KOHLI: An attacking player with a cool head, Virat Kohli has already earned a reputation as a level-headed and mature cricketer. The India Under-19 captain has scored a hundred in the World Cup and has 216 runs from five matches. A solid middle-order bat, he has also been successful with his medium pace in the tournament.         
	SREEVATS GOSWAMI: The wicketkeeper-batsman played a big role in Indias semi-final win over New Zealand. The lefthanders elegant strokeplay has given India the upperhand at the top of the order in the tournament. He has also been successful with the gloves. His allround show will be crucial to Indias chances in the final. The Liluah boy, who has made NCA his second home, idolises Adam Gilchrist.         
	WAYNE PARNELL: A left-handed batsman and mediumpacer with strong leadership qualities, Parnell is vital for South Africa. He was also part of South Africas squad for the 2006 World Cup in Sri Lanka. The experience hes gained over the years got him the captaincy for this edition and has so far proved to be worth it.         
	JONATHAN VANDIAR: A left-handed middle-order batsman who made his first-class debut for KwaZulu-Natal in January 2008, he has 183 runs from five matches. He has scored a century against Bangladesh in the lead-up to the tournament.                                                                                                                       
